III. Establishing the company's business strategy is not part of the "Monitoring Matters." Teacher Shan Hai considers this type of question relatively challenging, but it is one of the common approaches in setting exam questions. Candidates should pay a little attention to this. Essentially, you only need to follow the logic—"Monitoring Matters" does not concern your business strategy, so this option can be excluded.

**Monitoring Matters**

It is necessary to formulate and maintain appropriate policies and procedures to ensure that intermediaries and their staff comply with all applicable laws and regulatory requirements, as well as the intermediary's own internal policies and procedures.

Senior management should:

(a) **Establish and maintain an effective monitoring function that is independent of all operational and business functions and reports directly to senior management;**

(b) Ensure that staff performing the monitoring function possess the necessary skills, qualifications, and experience;

(c) Establish and implement policies and procedures to ensure that staff performing the monitoring function have access, as far as practicable, to all necessary records and documents from all business areas without hindrance;

(d) Require and assist staff performing the monitoring function to establish effective and comprehensive monitoring procedures covering:

(i) Legal and regulatory requirements, including licensing, registration, and financial resource requirements;

(ii) Record-keeping (please refer to Chapter 4, "Securities and Futures (Keeping of Records) Rules");

(iii) Business conduct;

(iv) Prevention of money laundering activities (please refer to Section 3 of this chapter);

(v) Internal control matters; and

(vi) Transactions of clients, the intermediary itself, and staff; these monitoring procedures should ensure that the intermediary complies with all requirements at all times;

(e) **Establish proper complaint handling procedures, which must be conducted in writing;**

(f) Establish mechanisms for staff performing the monitoring function to report immediately to senior management upon discovering serious breaches of:

(i) Legal and regulatory requirements; and

(ii) The intermediary's own policies and procedures; and

(g) Report immediately to the appropriate regulatory authorities if serious breaches of legal and regulatory requirements by the intermediary or its staff are discovered
